communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The 19 new confirmed and 182 new suspected cases in week 13 (23-29 Mar 2020) indicate that Lassa fever (LF) virus transmission is continuing but declining considerably. The graph in figure 6 indicates a peak of cases may have occurred in week 7. It will be interesting to see whether the decline in cases continues going forward. There are now 185 deaths among confirmed cases so far this year (2020). Fortunately, there are no newly infected healthcare workers during the current week (week 13).

The report above confirms that Ondo and Edo states have the majority of cases. The area affected remains at 27 states, but local governement areas increased to 126 with at least one case. Nigeria is into the period of the year when fewer cases usually occur, as illustrated in the graph in Figure 6 (available at the source URL above). There has been a peak in case numbers between weeks 1 and 11 (January-March) over the past 3 years, and it appears that this is the case again this year (2020).

Transmission of LF virus occurs when individuals are in contact with rodent reservoir host excreta or are within healthcare facilities. It is encouraging to learn that risk communications and community engagement activities have been scaled up across states using television, radio, print, social media, and other strategies for avoidance of contact with rodent virus reservoirs and their excreta.

Images of the rodent reservoirs of Lassa fever virus:
_Mastomys natalensis_: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/45326-Mastomys-natalensis
_Mastomys erythroleucus_ and _Hylomyscus pamfi_: http://punchng.com/nigerias-large-rat-population-threatens-lassa-fever-war/

Maps of Nigeria: http://www.un.org/Depts/Cartographic/map/profile/nigeria.pdf and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=7177542,62. - Mod.TY]
